"'''Shattered Glass'''" is a song recorded by American recording artist [[Britney Spears]]. The song was written by [[Dr. Luke|Lukasz "Dr. Luke" Gottwald]], [[Claude Kelly]], [[Benny Blanco|Benjamin "Benny Blanco" Levin]], and produced by Dr. Luke and Benny Blanco for Spears' sixth studio album, ''[[Circus (Britney Spears album)|Circus]]'' (2008). "Shattered Glass" is an up-tempo [[teen-pop]] and [[dance music|dance]] song with elements of [[disco]], while Spears' vocals have been [[Auto-Tune|Auto-Tuned]] on the track. Lyrically, the song is very emotional, with Spears singing of entrapment and self loathing in her relationship with fame.<ref name="NYTimesReview"/><ref name="NationalPost">{{cite web|url=http://network.nationalpost.com/np/blogs/theampersand/archive/2008/12/01/cd-review-the-devil-and-britney-spears.aspx|title=CD Review: Circus, Britney Spears|author=|first=Ben|last=Kaplan|date=2008-12-01|accessdate=2011-01-22|publisher=''[[National Post]]''}}</ref><ref name="Daily Global">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyglobal.com/2008/11/britney-spears-circus-pop-cd-review/|title=Britney Spears: Circus <U+2013> pop CD review|date=2011-11-25|accessdate=2011-01-22|publisher=''Daily Global''}}</ref>

Reception of the track from music critics was mixed, with some noting its dance and pop sound, while others called it "generic" and filler. Although the song was never released independently from ''Circus'', besides being released as a [[B-side]] to "[[Unusual You]]," it managed to peak on many of the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard charts|component charts]], including number seventy on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], seventy-five on the [[Canadian Hot 100]], and number fifty-seven on the [[Billboard Pop 100|''Billboard'' Pop 100]].

== Background and composition ==
{{Listen
|pos=left
|title = "Shattered Glass" (2008)
|filename = 05_Shattered_Glass.ogg
|description = A sample of the song containing Spears singing the chorus of the track. Her vocals in the song have been distorted through the use of Auto-Tune.
|format = [[Ogg]]
}}
The song was included as a [[B-side]] for "[[Unusual You]]", released as the final single from ''[[Circus (Britney Spears album)|Circus]]'' in Australia and New Zealand on September 15, 2009.<ref name="HungMedien">{{cite web|url=http://charts.org.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Britney+Spears&titel=Unusual+You&cat=s|title=Britney Spears - Unusual You|accessdate=2011-03-10|work=charts.org.nz|publisher=Hung Medien}}</ref><ref>{{Cite music release notes|Name=Unusual You |Type=single|Artist=Britney Spears|Year=2009|Format=AUS/NZ CD Single liner notes|Publisher=Jive Records|PID=86974 78842}}</ref> "Shattered Glass" is an up-tempo [[pop music|pop]] song with [[guitar]] [[rifts]], jagged and distorted vocals in the verses, and a melodic chorus.<ref name="About.comReview">{{cite web|url=http://dancemusic.about.com/od/reviews/fr/BritneySpearsCi.htm|title=Britney Spears - 'Circus'|author=|first=Ben|last=Norman|accessdate=2011-01-22|work=[[About.com]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]}}</ref> Spears' "robotic electro-sound", [[Auto-Tune|Auto-Tuned]] vocals on the track have drawn comparisons to her 2007 album ''[[Blackout (Britney Spears album)|Blackout]]'', though it has been noted by [[ABC News]]' Allan Raible that her vocals sound more "alive" than on the rest of ''Circus''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/allan_raible/2009/01/review-britney.html|title=Review: Britney Spears<U+2019> <U+201C>Circus<U+201D>|author=|first=Allan|last=Raible|date=2009-01-16|accessdate=2011-02-07|publisher=[[ABC News]]. ABC News Internet Ventures}}</ref> The song contains elements of [[teen pop]], [[electronic (music)|electronic]], and dance music.<ref name="NYTimesReview">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/01/arts/music/01choi.html?_r=1|title=Critics<U+2019> Choice - New CDs From - Britney Spears, Akon, Cynic, and John Escreet|author=|first=John|last=Pareles|date=2008-11-30|accessdate=2011-01-22|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''}}</ref> Lyrically, the song has varying emotions in its lyrics, speaking of flirting, betrayal, and a sense of entrapment as well as self loathing in her relationship with fame.<ref name="NYTimesReview" /><ref name="NationalPost"/><ref name="Daily Global"/> The song was written and produced by Lukasz "Dr. Luke" Gottwald, who is also working as co-executive producer on Spears' seventh studio album ''[[Femme Fatale (Britney Spears album)|Femme Fatale]]'', and Bejamin "Benny Blanco" Levin, with co-writing credits to Claude Kelly.<ref name="liner">{{cite album-notes|title=Circus|artist=Britney Spears|year=2008|publisher=[[Jive Records]]|format=Liner notes|publisherid=}}</ref> Background vocals were provided by Kelly and Windy Wagner.<ref name="liner"/>

== Reception ==
[[Image:If_you_seek_amy.jpg|thumb|upright|Britney Spears performing on her tour [[The Circus Starring Britney Spears]], in 2009]]
''[[Entertainment Weekly|Entertainment Weekly's]]'' Chris William said that "Dr. Luke and Max Martin [were] bringing their B game" to the track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20242634,00.html|title=Circus|Music|author=|first=Chris|last=William|date=2008-11-29|accessdate=2011-01-22|publisher=''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times|The New York Times']]'' John Pareles said the song and "[[Womanizer (song)|Womanizer]]," the lead single single from ''Circus'', "use their pulsing electro arrangements for teen-pop tales of flirting and betrayal."<ref name="NYTimesReview"/> [[PopMatters]], however, called the song part of the "mid-album slump", saying that "she reveals her proclivity for the same stomping, unsubtle beefiness of 'Womanizer', but there<U+2019>s a notable lapse in quality."<ref name="popmatters">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/66714-britney-spears-circus/|title=Britney Spears: Circus|author=|first=Mike|last=Newmark|date=2008-12-10|accessdate=2011-01-22|publisher=[[PopMatters]]}}</ref> Jim Farber from ''[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]'' said the song had "real bubblegum snap"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/2008/11/30/2008-11-30_britney_spears_circus_is_a_3ring_hit_.html|title=Britney Spears 'Circus' is a 3-ring hit|author=|first=Jim|last=Farber|date=2008-12-02|accessdate=2011-01-22|publisher=''[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]''}}</ref> while Ben Noramn from [[About.com]] called it a "beautiful upbeat pop tune."<ref name="About.comReview" /> ''[[National Post|National Post's]]'' Ben Kaplan called the song a "kiss-off guitar-laden hard disco."<ref name="NationalPost"/>

Despite only being included as a B-side for "Unusual You", the song managed to chart on many of the ''Billboard'' charts. Due to [[music download|digital downloads]] from ''Circus'', the song managed to peak at number seventy on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart on the week of December 15, 2008 before dropping off the next week.<ref name="ChartHistoryAllMusic"/> "Shattered Glass" charted at number fifty-seven on the [[Pop Songs]] and number twenty-nine on the [[Hot Digital Songs]].<ref name="ChartHistoryAllMusic" /> It received similar reception in Canada, debuting at number seventy-five on the [[Canadian Hot 100]] and number thirty-six on the [[Hot Canadian Digital Singles]] in the same week.<ref name="ChartHistoryAllMusic"/><ref name=Billboard>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/canadian-hot-100?chartDate=2008-12-20&order=gainer|title=Canadian Hot 100|date=2008-12-20|accessdate=2011-03-10|work=''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]}}</ref>

